complex relationship with Arthurian legend has been surprisingly neglected, and this volume is the first to be dedicated to it. The essays cover the period between the appearance inca. 1136 of Geoffrey of Monmouth's Historia Regum Britanniae and the accession of James VI to the English throne as James I in 1603 - five centuries of precarious Scottish independence during which the relationship of theScots and the English, as refracted through Arthurian legend, is at its most turbulent and changeable. The approaches are both literary and historical, covering such topics as the direct responses of early Scottish historians to the challenges set by Geoffrey's work, Arthurian literature written in Scots, the circulation of other Arthurian material in Scotland, and the portrayal of Scotland and the Scots in English and French Arthurian texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxSources. 0aBritonsxKings and rulersxFolklore. 0aLegendsxHistory and criticismzScotland. 0aRomances, EnglishxSources. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBawcutt, Priscilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainer, Sergi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPurdie, Rhiannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPurdie, Rhiannon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoyan, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoyan, Nicola, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRushton, Co